1
00:06:02,042 --> 00:06:02,974
<i>? Well, now?</i>

2
00:06:03,043 --> 00:06:05,204
<i>? Ain't this
an elegant neighborhood??</i>

3
00:06:05,278 --> 00:06:08,304
<i>? All the residents
dress so fine?</i>

4
00:06:08,381 --> 00:06:13,683
<i>? One day off the boat am I
with a job that's nearly mine?</i>

5
00:06:13,753 --> 00:06:16,779
<i>? 'Tis a job with
an elegant millionaire?</i>

6
00:06:16,856 --> 00:06:19,791
<i>? And his elegant family?</i>

7
00:06:19,859 --> 00:06:31,635
<i>? Today I move from immigrant
to high society?</i>

8
00:06:31,705 --> 00:06:33,468
Now, you may call that luck.

9
00:06:33,540 --> 00:06:35,167
And you may call it fortune.

10
00:06:35,241 --> 00:06:37,106
But me, meself...

11
00:06:37,444 --> 00:06:43,178
<i>? I call it?</i>

12
00:06:43,249 --> 00:06:45,843
<i>? Fortuosity?</i>

13
00:06:45,919 --> 00:06:48,717
<i>? That's me byword?</i>

14
00:06:48,788 --> 00:06:50,653
<i>? Fortuosity?</i>

15
00:06:50,724 --> 00:06:53,887
<i>? Me twinkle-in-the-eye word?</i>

16
00:06:53,960 --> 00:06:59,159
<i>? Sometimes castles
fall to the ground?</i>

17
00:06:59,232 --> 00:07:04,864
<i>? But that's where
four-leaf clovers abound?</i>

18
00:07:05,338 --> 00:07:07,067
<i>? Fortuosity?</i>

19
00:07:08,174 --> 00:07:10,699
<i>? Lucky chances?</i>

20
00:07:10,777 --> 00:07:16,875
<i>? Fortuitious little
happy happenstances?</i>

21
00:07:26,860 --> 00:07:32,389
<i>? I don't worry
'cause everywhere I see?</i>

22
00:07:32,465 --> 00:07:37,835
<i>? That every bit of life
is lit by fortuosity?</i>

23
00:08:04,531 --> 00:08:07,364
<i>? Fortuosity?</i>

24
00:08:07,433 --> 00:08:09,594
<i>? That's me own word?</i>

25
00:08:09,669 --> 00:08:11,796
<i>? Fortuosity?</i>

26
00:08:11,871 --> 00:08:15,307
<i>? Me never-feel-alone word?</i>

27
00:08:15,375 --> 00:08:20,244
<i>? Round the corner,
under a tree?</i>

28
00:08:20,313 --> 00:08:23,510
<i>? Good fortune's waitin'?</i>

29
00:08:23,583 --> 00:08:26,416
<i>? Just wait and see?</i>

30
00:08:26,486 --> 00:08:29,387
<i>? Fortuosity?</i>

31
00:08:29,455 --> 00:08:32,015
<i>? Lucky chances?</i>

32
00:08:32,091 --> 00:08:37,085
<i>? Fortuitious little
happy happenstances?</i>

33
00:08:37,163 --> 00:08:42,396
<i>? I keep smilin'
'cause my philosophy?</i>

34
00:08:42,468 --> 00:08:45,062
<i>? Is do your best
and leave the rest?</i>

35
00:08:45,138 --> 00:08:48,665
<i>? To fortuosity?</i>

36
00:09:43,296 --> 00:09:48,393
<i>? I keep smilin'
'cause my philosophy?</i>

37
00:09:48,468 --> 00:09:51,130
<i>? Is do your best
and leave the rest?</i>

38
00:09:51,204 --> 00:10:00,044
<i>? To fortuosity?</i>

39
00:10:00,113 --> 00:10:01,910
Good day to you, ma'am.

40
00:10:02,415 --> 00:10:05,680
Would this be the home of
Mr. Anthony J. Drexel Biddle?

41
00:10:05,752 --> 00:10:06,548
It would.

42
00:10:06,619 --> 00:10:09,747
I've come to be interviewed
for the position of the butler.

43
00:10:09,822 --> 00:10:11,653
Mrs. Biddle
does the interviewin'.

44
00:10:11,724 --> 00:10:13,021
She's not at home just now.

45
00:10:13,092 --> 00:10:15,890
But I had an appointment.
The Mayflower Employment Agency.

46
00:10:15,962 --> 00:10:18,522
I'll tell Mrs. Biddle that
you were put out about it.

47
00:10:18,598 --> 00:10:20,532
Oh.
Not at all.

48
00:10:20,600 --> 00:10:23,535
I'd be pleased to call again.

49
00:10:24,637 --> 00:10:25,865
Good day to ya.

50
00:10:25,939 --> 00:10:28,533
What part of Ireland?

51
00:10:29,142 --> 00:10:30,336
County Tyrone.

52
00:10:30,410 --> 00:10:32,173
Just new here, are ya?

53
00:10:32,245 --> 00:10:34,509
The day before yesterday.

54
00:10:34,580 --> 00:10:38,380
Oh, well, perhaps you'd like
to wait in the kitchen.

55
00:10:38,451 --> 00:10:40,749
Mrs. Biddle
will be comin' home soon.

56
00:10:40,820 --> 00:10:43,288
That's very kind of you.
Thank you very much.

57
00:10:59,872 --> 00:11:02,932
Faith, 'tis a grand place
you have here.

58
00:11:03,009 --> 00:11:04,943
I'm the housekeeper here.

59
00:11:05,011 --> 00:11:06,706
Me name's Mrs. Worth.

60
00:11:06,779 --> 00:11:08,246
Mine's John Lawless.

61
00:11:08,314 --> 00:11:10,714
This way, John Lawless.

62
00:11:13,653 --> 00:11:15,917
Have a seat,
and I'll pour you some coffee.

63
00:11:15,989 --> 00:11:17,616
Don't you be troubling yourself.

64
00:11:17,690 --> 00:11:18,714
No trouble.

65
00:11:18,791 --> 00:11:20,759
There's a pot
brewing on the stove.

66
00:11:20,827 --> 00:11:22,419
Sit down.

67
00:11:25,131 --> 00:11:27,429
Would you be from Ireland
yourself, Mrs. Worth?

68
00:11:27,500 --> 00:11:29,695
I came over as young girl.

69
00:11:29,769 --> 00:11:31,464
Not long ago, then.

70
00:11:34,140 --> 00:11:36,836
Tell me, Mrs. Worth, what
became of the last butler?

71
00:11:36,909 --> 00:11:38,638
I couldn't say.

72
00:11:38,711 --> 00:11:40,770
He left in the dead of night

73
00:11:40,847 --> 00:11:44,374
after being here
less than a month.

74
00:11:44,817 --> 00:11:47,342
We've got a servant problem
in this house.

75
00:11:47,420 --> 00:11:49,047
No use sayin' we don't.

76
00:11:49,122 --> 00:11:51,249
Must be hard working
for the very rich.

77
00:11:51,324 --> 00:11:53,952
I mean, they're accustomed
to havin' things just so.

78
00:11:54,027 --> 00:11:56,757
That's not exactly the problem.

79
00:11:57,864 --> 00:11:59,991
The wage is very low.

80
00:12:00,066 --> 00:12:04,002
No, the Biddles
are generous enough.

81
00:12:04,670 --> 00:12:05,762
Long hours, then?

82
00:12:05,838 --> 00:12:08,363
I wouldn't say so.

83
00:12:10,143 --> 00:12:11,542
There's a gorgeous sight.

84
00:12:11,611 --> 00:12:13,476
Are you getting ready
for a party?

85
00:12:13,546 --> 00:12:17,107
No, Mr. Biddle's
on a chocolate-cake diet.

86
00:12:17,183 --> 00:12:18,445
I beg your pardon?

87
00:12:18,518 --> 00:12:19,780
Cordelia!

88
00:12:19,852 --> 00:12:21,581
He says it's the perfect food,

89
00:12:21,654 --> 00:12:25,351
containing every
essential element.

90
00:12:25,691 --> 00:12:26,783
Where is Mrs. Biddle?

91
00:12:26,859 --> 00:12:28,224
She's gone shopping.

92
00:12:28,294 --> 00:12:29,693
Blast!
And Cordy?

93
00:12:29,762 --> 00:12:31,457
- I couldn't say.
- And the boys?

94
00:12:31,531 --> 00:12:33,294
I haven't seen them since lunch.

95
00:12:33,366 --> 00:12:34,663
At a time like this.

96
00:12:34,734 --> 00:12:36,065
No one!

97
00:12:36,135 --> 00:12:38,194
Is there something
I could do, Mr. Biddle?

98
00:12:38,271 --> 00:12:39,932
Yes.
You can call Dr. Donleavy.

99
00:12:40,006 --> 00:12:41,837
Tell him I've been bit
by an alligator.

100
00:12:41,908 --> 00:12:43,569
Oh, dear!

101
00:12:45,445 --> 00:12:47,345
Might as well live alone.

102
00:12:47,780 --> 00:12:48,804
Are you a married man?

103
00:12:48,881 --> 00:12:49,848
Me, sir?
No, sir.

104
00:12:49,916 --> 00:12:51,713
Then you wouldn't understand.

105
00:12:52,452 --> 00:12:54,511
<i>? I've been bit on my finger?</i>

106
00:12:54,587 --> 00:12:56,350
<i>? It could have been my leg?</i>

107
00:12:56,422 --> 00:12:57,980
<i>? It could have been my head?</i>

108
00:12:58,057 --> 00:12:59,957
<i>? I might have died?</i>

109
00:13:00,026 --> 00:13:01,823
<i>? In a time of mortal peril?</i>

110
00:13:01,894 --> 00:13:03,725
<i>? Any man should expect?</i>

111
00:13:03,796 --> 00:13:06,890
<i>? That his family will come
rushing to his side?</i>

112
00:13:06,966 --> 00:13:09,196
<i>? What's wrong with that??</i>

113
00:13:09,268 --> 00:13:11,065
<i>? What's wrong with that??</i>

114
00:13:11,137 --> 00:13:13,037
<i>? My family rushing
to my side?</i>

115
00:13:13,106 --> 00:13:14,937
<i>? What's wrong with that??</i>

116
00:13:15,007 --> 00:13:17,134
Oh, not a thing, sir, I'm sure.

117
00:13:22,215 --> 00:13:24,445
<i>? I'm a good-hearted husband?</i>

118
00:13:24,517 --> 00:13:26,144
<i>? I'm generous and kind?</i>

119
00:13:26,219 --> 00:13:29,313
<i>? No wife could have
a life as free of cares?</i>

120
00:13:29,388 --> 00:13:32,380
<i>? So when a good-hearted
husband has been bit?</i>

121
00:13:32,458 --> 00:13:33,516
<i>? It's only right?</i>

122
00:13:33,593 --> 00:13:37,029
<i>? That his wife should share
the agony he bears?</i>

123
00:13:37,096 --> 00:13:38,859
<i>? What's wrong with that??</i>

124
00:13:38,931 --> 00:13:40,796
<i>? What's wrong with that??</i>

125
00:13:40,867 --> 00:13:42,892
<i>? I want my wife
to share my life?</i>

126
00:13:42,969 --> 00:13:44,937
<i>? What's wrong with that??</i>

127
00:13:45,004 --> 00:13:46,232
Cordelia!

128
00:13:48,241 --> 00:13:49,265
Well, now.

129
00:13:49,342 --> 00:13:52,436
Now, that answers a whole slew
of questions, don't it?

130
00:13:52,512 --> 00:13:54,070
Cordy!

131
00:13:54,147 --> 00:13:55,705
Boys!

132
00:13:56,616 --> 00:13:58,311
Blast!

133
00:13:58,384 --> 00:14:01,148
<i>? Here in this house
I'm raising?</i>

134
00:14:01,220 --> 00:14:03,120
<i>? Three strong,
intelligent children?</i>

135
00:14:03,189 --> 00:14:06,886
<i>? Where are they now in
their father's time of need??</i>

136
00:14:06,959 --> 00:14:08,824
<i>? I give them private tutors?</i>

137
00:14:08,895 --> 00:14:10,556
<i>? The finest
physical trainers?</i>

138
00:14:10,630 --> 00:14:12,928
<i>? All in vain?</i>

139
00:14:13,266 --> 00:14:15,291
Ohh, the pain!

140
00:14:16,035 --> 00:14:17,662
<i>? I believe in the Bible?</i>

141
00:14:17,737 --> 00:14:19,637
<i>? I believe in Uncle Sam?</i>

142
00:14:19,705 --> 00:14:23,334
<i>? And as sure
as Old Glory waves above?</i>

143
00:14:23,409 --> 00:14:26,936
<i>? I believe a man who's bitten
has the right to demand?</i>

144
00:14:27,013 --> 00:14:30,642
<i>? That his family give him
sympathy and love?</i>

145
00:14:30,716 --> 00:14:32,513
<i>? What's wrong with that??</i>

146
00:14:32,585 --> 00:14:34,553
<i>? What's wrong with that??</i>

147
00:14:34,620 --> 00:14:39,751
<i>? The flag above,
the Bible, and love?</i>

148
00:14:39,825 --> 00:14:41,952
<i>? What's wrong with that??</i>

149
00:14:42,028 --> 00:14:43,086
- Hello, Papa.
- Cordy!

150
00:14:43,162 --> 00:14:44,356
Where have you been?

151
00:14:44,430 --> 00:14:46,694
Out in the stable
with Tony and Liv.

152
00:14:46,766 --> 00:14:49,599
- Is something wrong?
- Yes, something's wrong.

153
00:14:49,669 --> 00:14:51,830
What were you doing shaving
at this time of day?

154
00:14:51,904 --> 00:14:52,996
I haven't been shaving.

155
00:14:53,072 --> 00:14:54,972
And since when do
I shave my finger?

156
00:14:55,041 --> 00:14:56,633
You don't shave your ear either.

157
00:14:56,709 --> 00:14:58,540
- But last week you cut it.
- That's different.

158
00:14:58,611 --> 00:15:00,772
The ear is in the general
vicinity of the face.

159
00:15:00,846 --> 00:15:02,336
So's the finger
when you're shaving.

160
00:15:02,415 --> 00:15:04,042
It's a bite, blast it!

161
00:15:04,116 --> 00:15:05,310
- No.
- Yes.

162
00:15:05,384 --> 00:15:06,942
- Who?
- George.

163
00:15:07,019 --> 00:15:10,216
Turned on me just like that
after all these years.

164
00:15:11,324 --> 00:15:15,192
Well, it's really
not such a bad bite.

165
00:15:15,261 --> 00:15:17,092
Is that all you have to say?

166
00:15:17,163 --> 00:15:19,131
There's some antiseptic
in the emergency kit.

167
00:15:19,198 --> 00:15:20,859
- And some bandages.
- Wait a minute.

168
00:15:20,933 --> 00:15:23,367
Where are you going?
It's time for Bible class.

169
00:15:23,436 --> 00:15:24,698
Yes, I know.

170
00:15:24,770 --> 00:15:26,601
But you'll have to do
without me today.

171
00:15:26,672 --> 00:15:29,106
I have an engagement.

172
00:15:29,475 --> 00:15:32,876
Dr. Donleavy's somewhere between
his office and the hospital.

173
00:15:32,945 --> 00:15:34,606
Keep trying.

174
00:15:34,680 --> 00:15:35,772
Oh, what are you doing?

175
00:15:35,848 --> 00:15:37,213
Me, sir?
Not a thing, sir.

176
00:15:37,283 --> 00:15:38,841
- Well, do something.
- Yes, sir.

177
00:15:38,918 --> 00:15:40,078
Blasted alligator.

178
00:15:40,152 --> 00:15:42,313
- I beg your pardon.
- Treated him like a son.

179
00:15:42,388 --> 00:15:44,219
What exactly would you
like me to do?

180
00:15:44,290 --> 00:15:47,191
Tell the boys to bring in
that emergency kit.

181
00:15:47,860 --> 00:15:50,658
Out the back door,
across the yard to the stable.

182
00:15:50,730 --> 00:15:52,391
Mr. Tony.
Mr. Livingston.

183
00:15:52,465 --> 00:15:54,365
Mr. Tony and Mr. Livingston.

184
00:15:54,433 --> 00:15:56,765
Blasted Benedict Arnold.
That's what he is.

185
00:16:02,875 --> 00:16:03,569
Yes?

186
00:16:03,643 --> 00:16:06,009
Would you tell Miss Biddle
Mr. Taylor is calling?

187
00:16:06,078 --> 00:16:08,876
- Mr. Who?
- Mr. Charles Taylor.

188
00:16:09,415 --> 00:16:11,815
Miss Biddle is expecting me.

189
00:16:19,992 --> 00:16:21,482
Cordy!

190
00:16:35,608 --> 00:16:38,338
Dr. Donleavy must have stopped
to make a house call.

191
00:16:38,411 --> 00:16:39,469
I could be dying.

192
00:16:39,545 --> 00:16:41,240
Indeed you could.

193
00:16:41,847 --> 00:16:43,508
Where's that blasted antiseptic?

194
00:16:43,582 --> 00:16:44,571
Here you are, Pa.

195
00:16:44,650 --> 00:16:46,880
- It's about time.
- We came as soon as we heard.

196
00:16:46,952 --> 00:16:49,318
I left word with
the doctor to call.

197
00:16:49,388 --> 00:16:50,412
What happened, Pa?

198
00:16:50,489 --> 00:16:51,513
Was it really George?

199
00:16:51,590 --> 00:16:52,557
Gentle old George?

200
00:16:52,625 --> 00:16:54,616
Yes, it was gentle old George.

201
00:16:54,694 --> 00:16:57,288
Hey, Pa, what's
Charlie Taylor doing here?

202
00:16:57,363 --> 00:16:59,058
He came to see Cordy.

203
00:16:59,131 --> 00:17:01,361
The answer to a maiden's prayer.

204
00:17:03,569 --> 00:17:05,560
What do you know
about maidens' prayers?

205
00:17:05,638 --> 00:17:07,503
Nothing, Pa.
It's just an expression.

206
00:17:07,573 --> 00:17:08,505
Oh.

207
00:17:08,574 --> 00:17:09,666
But Charlie Taylor?

208
00:17:09,742 --> 00:17:12,176
- Cordy can do better than that.
- I'm sure she can.

209
00:17:12,244 --> 00:17:14,371
When the time comes.

210
00:17:24,090 --> 00:17:26,081
That's pretty good.
Going into vaudeville?

211
00:17:26,158 --> 00:17:27,785
Hi, Tony.
Long time, no see.

212
00:17:27,860 --> 00:17:30,021
- This is my brother, Liv.
- Hiya, sport.

213
00:17:30,096 --> 00:17:31,563
Hi.

214
00:17:32,064 --> 00:17:34,089
- Say, that man in the hall.
- Yeah?

215
00:17:34,166 --> 00:17:35,599
That wasn't your father, was it?

216
00:17:35,668 --> 00:17:38,603
- Who did you think it was?
- I thought he was some kind...

217
00:17:38,671 --> 00:17:40,195
Uh, uh, uh.

218
00:17:40,873 --> 00:17:42,773
Hey, caramel!

219
00:17:44,310 --> 00:17:45,607
They're for Cordy, sport.

220
00:17:45,678 --> 00:17:46,838
Cordy hates caramels.

221
00:17:46,912 --> 00:17:48,277
They stick in her retainer.

222
00:17:48,347 --> 00:17:49,371
But I like caramel.

223
00:17:49,448 --> 00:17:50,881
So does Tony.
Don't you, sport?

224
00:17:50,950 --> 00:17:52,315
Oh, love 'em.

225
00:17:53,219 --> 00:17:56,052
Okay, fellas, that's enough.

226
00:17:56,122 --> 00:17:59,057
Charlie! You've been hiding
your light under a bushel.

227
00:17:59,125 --> 00:18:01,320
Liv, you should feel that.

228
00:18:01,827 --> 00:18:04,591
Hey! What weight do you
fight at, Charlie?

229
00:18:04,663 --> 00:18:06,221
- Fight?
- Boxing.

230
00:18:06,298 --> 00:18:08,391
You do box, don't you?

231
00:18:08,467 --> 00:18:11,095
I prefer other sports.

232
00:18:11,170 --> 00:18:12,467
You don't do it at all?

233
00:18:12,538 --> 00:18:13,505
No.

234
00:18:13,572 --> 00:18:15,540
Liv, he doesn't do it at all.

235
00:18:15,608 --> 00:18:17,098
Aw, Charlie.

236
00:18:17,176 --> 00:18:18,438
You're in trouble.

237
00:18:18,511 --> 00:18:20,103
I don't understand.

238
00:18:20,179 --> 00:18:22,704
Well, if you've got
your eye on Cordy...

239
00:18:22,782 --> 00:18:25,273
<i>? Remember Harry Applegate??</i>

240
00:18:25,351 --> 00:18:28,252
<i>? Yeah, he took
Cordy on a date?</i>

241
00:18:28,320 --> 00:18:30,948
<i>? Oh, what a dapper Dan?</i>

242
00:18:31,023 --> 00:18:33,321
<i>? Pearly teeth and tennis tan?</i>

243
00:18:33,392 --> 00:18:34,416
Remember him well.

244
00:18:34,493 --> 00:18:37,326
<i>? Thought he was a Romeo?</i>

245
00:18:37,396 --> 00:18:40,160
<i>? Tried to kiss our sis,
and, oh!?</i>

246
00:18:40,232 --> 00:18:42,962
<i>? Harry ducked, but too late?</i>

247
00:18:43,035 --> 00:18:45,902
<i>? Father bought him
an upper plate?</i>

248
00:18:45,971 --> 00:18:48,769
<i>? Watch your footwork?</i>

249
00:18:48,841 --> 00:18:51,639
<i>? Better learn
to bob and weave?</i>

250
00:18:51,710 --> 00:18:55,544
<i>? Sister Cordy's
got dynamite up her sleeve?</i>

251
00:18:55,614 --> 00:18:56,808
<i>? What a jab?</i>

252
00:18:56,882 --> 00:18:58,611
<i>? Dynamite up her sleeve?</i>

253
00:18:58,684 --> 00:18:59,742
<i>? What a hook?</i>

254
00:18:59,819 --> 00:19:01,446
<i>? Dynamite up her sleeve?</i>

255
00:19:01,520 --> 00:19:03,215
<i>? Keep your guard up?</i>

256
00:19:03,289 --> 00:19:05,553
Charlie, never lead it
with your right.

257
00:19:05,624 --> 00:19:07,148
You'll get killed that way.

258
00:19:07,226 --> 00:19:09,421
Look, fellas,
let's forget the whole thing.

259
00:19:09,495 --> 00:19:11,087
I didn't come here to do this.

260
00:19:11,163 --> 00:19:13,791
<i>? Archie Baxter
came here twice?</i>

261
00:19:13,866 --> 00:19:16,528
<i>? First time out,
he acted nice?</i>

262
00:19:16,602 --> 00:19:19,230
<i>? Romance was in the air?</i>

263
00:19:19,305 --> 00:19:21,739
<i>? Oh, they made a lovely pair?</i>

264
00:19:21,807 --> 00:19:22,739
Beautiful.

265
00:19:22,808 --> 00:19:25,174
<i>? Second date, it was a dance?</i>

266
00:19:25,244 --> 00:19:28,577
<i>? He grabbed her tight,
this was his chance?</i>

267
00:19:28,647 --> 00:19:31,241
<i>? Cordy only bruised
that sport?</i>

268
00:19:31,317 --> 00:19:33,478
<i>? Father settled it
out of court?</i>

269
00:19:33,552 --> 00:19:34,348
So...

270
00:19:34,420 --> 00:19:36,945
<i>? Watch your footwork?</i>

271
00:19:37,022 --> 00:19:39,547
<i>? Better learn
to bob and weave?</i>

272
00:19:39,625 --> 00:19:43,959
<i>? Sister Cordy's
got dynamite up her sleeve?</i>

273
00:19:44,029 --> 00:19:45,291
<i>? What a fake?</i>

274
00:19:45,364 --> 00:19:46,922
<i>? Dynamite up her sleeve?</i>

275
00:19:46,999 --> 00:19:48,057
<i>? What an uppercut?</i>

276
00:19:48,133 --> 00:19:53,070
<i>? Dynamite up her sleeve?</i>

277
00:20:02,114 --> 00:20:03,342
Uh-oh.

278
00:20:03,415 --> 00:20:04,746
- Charlie.
- Charlie?

279
00:20:04,817 --> 00:20:06,785
- Hey, Charlie, wake up.
- Are you hurt?

280
00:20:06,852 --> 00:20:08,683
Tony? Livingston?

281
00:20:08,754 --> 00:20:11,188
Come on, it's time
for Bible class.

282
00:20:11,257 --> 00:20:12,383
What happened?

283
00:20:12,458 --> 00:20:14,517
He dropped his left.

284
00:20:14,593 --> 00:20:15,719
Oh.

285
00:20:19,231 --> 00:20:21,256
You better get some ice.

286
00:20:25,504 --> 00:20:30,134
And get some beefsteak.

287
00:20:43,889 --> 00:20:45,356
Charlie?

288
00:20:46,125 --> 00:20:47,456
Charlie!

289
00:20:48,260 --> 00:20:51,195
Well, don't you look pretty!

290
00:20:51,263 --> 00:20:52,560
Papa, how could you?

291
00:20:52,631 --> 00:20:53,962
How could I what?

292
00:20:54,033 --> 00:20:56,263
It's no wonder
I never have any callers.

293
00:20:56,335 --> 00:20:59,133
- Oh, now, wait a minute.
- People are afraid to come here.

294
00:20:59,204 --> 00:21:00,694
I didn't hurt the young sap.

295
00:21:00,773 --> 00:21:01,705
Sap?

296
00:21:01,774 --> 00:21:04,607
Charlie Taylor's only
the most popular boy in town.

297
00:21:06,478 --> 00:21:07,740
Oh, here he comes.

298
00:21:07,813 --> 00:21:09,747
Charlie, are you all right?

299
00:21:09,815 --> 00:21:11,874
Sure, he's all right.
Come on, Charlie.

300
00:21:11,951 --> 00:21:14,078
- Thataboy.
- I'm so sorry, Charlie.

301
00:21:14,153 --> 00:21:15,518
There's no serious damage.

302
00:21:15,588 --> 00:21:17,385
He'll have a black eye
for a couple of days.

303
00:21:17,456 --> 00:21:19,185
- Ooh!
- Can I get you something?

304
00:21:19,258 --> 00:21:20,486
I sent for some raw meat.

305
00:21:20,559 --> 00:21:22,254
How about a cold drink, Charlie?

306
00:21:22,328 --> 00:21:24,558
Oh!
Oh, thank you.

307
00:21:24,630 --> 00:21:27,531
Charlie, why don't you sit
in this comfortable chair?

308
00:21:27,600 --> 00:21:30,433
And I'll see if
I can get you some iced tea.

309
00:21:30,502 --> 00:21:33,130
Or would you like
a piece of chocolate cake?

310
00:21:33,205 --> 00:21:36,138
Charlie!

311
00:21:40,079 --> 00:21:41,046
Gee, we're sorry.

312
00:21:41,113 --> 00:21:42,740
We didn't mean to do it.

313
00:21:42,815 --> 00:21:44,373
We told him
to keep his guard up.

314
00:21:44,450 --> 00:21:47,010
You see, Cordy, I had
nothing to do with it.

315
00:21:48,754 --> 00:21:50,381
Didn't you?

316
00:21:50,456 --> 00:21:52,219
Like father, like son.

317
00:21:52,291 --> 00:21:54,521
You're all three the same.

318
00:21:54,593 --> 00:21:56,857
Always having your sport
no matter what.

319
00:21:56,929 --> 00:21:59,420
Always ready for a fight.

320
00:21:59,498 --> 00:22:00,658
Oh, Cordy, we didn't...

321
00:22:00,733 --> 00:22:03,531
Don't touch me.
I'll flatten you!

322
00:22:04,203 --> 00:22:05,500
Cordy.

323
00:22:08,440 --> 00:22:09,907
Cordy, wait.

324
00:22:14,013 --> 00:22:15,776
Blast it!

325
00:22:42,941 --> 00:22:47,401
<i>? Oh,
Miss Cordelia Drexel Biddle?</i>

326
00:22:47,479 --> 00:22:52,576
<i>? I thought I knew you well?</i>

327
00:22:52,651 --> 00:22:57,384
<i>? But now,
Miss Cordelia Drexel Biddle?</i>

328
00:22:57,456 --> 00:23:05,124
<i>? I just can't tell?</i>

329
00:23:05,197 --> 00:23:14,765
<i>? Are you valentine candy
or bo xing gloves??</i>

330
00:23:14,840 --> 00:23:23,339
<i>? Lately you seem
very strange?</i>

331
00:23:23,415 --> 00:23:30,321
<i>? What in the world's
coming over you??</i>

332
00:23:30,389 --> 00:23:37,886
<i>? Everything's starting
to change?</i>

333
00:23:37,963 --> 00:23:46,769
<i>? Are you sonnets by Shelley
or Rover Boys??</i>

334
00:23:46,839 --> 00:23:55,611
<i>? Once any answer would do?</i>

335
00:23:55,681 --> 00:24:03,588
<i>? Why are you
suddenly wondering?</i>

336
00:24:03,655 --> 00:24:10,356
<i>? Which kind of someone
are you??</i>

337
00:24:10,429 --> 00:24:19,133
<i>? Is a boy meant to spar with
or gaze at a star with??</i>

338
00:24:19,204 --> 00:24:26,804
<i>? Should you kiss him
or blacken his eye??</i>

339
00:24:26,879 --> 00:24:31,441
<i>? Now, if he buys you roses?</i>

340
00:24:31,517 --> 00:24:43,054
<i>? A right to the nose is really
not quite the proper reply?</i>

341
00:24:43,128 --> 00:24:51,331
<i>? You're so lost
in the middle of in-between?</i>

342
00:24:51,403 --> 00:24:59,606
<i>? Is your destiny canvas
or crepe de Chine??</i>

343
00:24:59,678 --> 00:25:12,955
<i>? Will you someday be someone
that somebody loves??</i>

344
00:25:13,025 --> 00:25:22,491
<i>? Are you valentine candy
or...?</i>

345
00:25:24,803 --> 00:25:32,642
<i>? Bo xing gloves??</i>

346
00:25:36,448 --> 00:25:38,279
Mrs. Worth,
I'm not a one to pry,

347
00:25:38,350 --> 00:25:40,443
but I can't help wondering
some things.

348
00:25:40,519 --> 00:25:42,282
Yes, Mr. Lawless?

349
00:25:42,354 --> 00:25:44,754
<i>? Board by board?</i>

350
00:25:44,823 --> 00:25:47,189
Is it forever like this?

351
00:25:47,259 --> 00:25:48,886
Like what?

352
00:25:50,362 --> 00:25:53,695
Ha, that must be
Dr. Donleavy at last.

353
00:25:54,766 --> 00:25:59,794
<i>? Body and mind of mortal man?</i>

354
00:26:00,372 --> 00:26:03,637
It isn't as if this was
the only job in Philadelphia.

355
00:26:04,309 --> 00:26:07,642
Well, not for
a likable lad like meself.

356
00:26:08,680 --> 00:26:13,845
<i>? Fashion the framework
board by board?</i>

357
00:26:14,920 --> 00:26:16,217
Mrs. Worth?

358
00:26:16,288 --> 00:26:18,449
I've decided
to run along for now.

359
00:26:18,523 --> 00:26:21,253
Perhaps I can call another day.

360
00:26:22,127 --> 00:26:23,719
Perhaps.

361
00:26:27,933 --> 00:26:28,865
Who are you?

362
00:26:28,934 --> 00:26:30,231
John Lawless.

363
00:26:30,302 --> 00:26:32,930
A professional pugilist,
no doubt.

364
00:26:33,005 --> 00:26:34,165
Ma'am?

365
00:26:34,239 --> 00:26:35,604
Did you come here to fight?

366
00:26:35,674 --> 00:26:38,438
Oh, no, ma'am, I came
about the butler's position.

367
00:26:38,510 --> 00:26:40,137
Then announce me.

368
00:26:40,212 --> 00:26:42,373
And take off your hat
in the house.

369
00:27:00,365 --> 00:27:04,893
<i>? Strengthen the dwelling
of the Lord?</i>

370
00:27:04,970 --> 00:27:09,669
<i>? Fashion the framework
board by board?</i>

371
00:27:09,741 --> 00:27:14,144
<i>? Here in his image
now we stand?</i>

372
00:27:14,212 --> 00:27:18,308
<i>? Building his fortress
strong and grand?</i>

373
00:27:18,383 --> 00:27:20,248
<i>? It is written that the?</i>

374
00:27:20,319 --> 00:27:24,585
<i>? Body and mind of mortal man?</i>

375
00:27:24,656 --> 00:27:28,649
<i>? Should walk in the spirit
of his master plan?</i>

376
00:27:28,727 --> 00:27:29,819
Mr. Biddle?

377
00:27:29,895 --> 00:27:31,726
There's a lady
in the music room.

378
00:27:31,797 --> 00:27:32,729
A lady?

379
00:27:32,798 --> 00:27:35,198
She didn't give a name.
Like there was no need.

380
00:27:35,267 --> 00:27:37,735
Aunt Mary.
Tell her there's nobody at home.

381
00:27:37,803 --> 00:27:38,531
But, sir...

382
00:27:38,603 --> 00:27:40,127
<i>? It is written that the?</i>

383
00:27:40,205 --> 00:27:44,403
<i>? Body and mind of mortal man?</i>

384
00:27:44,476 --> 00:27:48,572
<i>? Should walk in the spirit
of his master plan?</i>

385
00:27:48,647 --> 00:27:53,346
<i>? So we must strengthen
the dwelling of the Lord?</i>

386
00:27:58,190 --> 00:28:00,681
I'm afraid
there's no one here, ma'am.

387
00:28:00,759 --> 00:28:02,556
No one here?

388
00:28:04,997 --> 00:28:07,158
No one at all save
Mrs. Worth and meself.

389
00:28:07,232 --> 00:28:09,325
And as for me, I...

390
00:28:09,401 --> 00:28:15,465
<i>? It is written that the body
and mind of mortal man?</i>

391
00:28:15,540 --> 00:28:18,634
<i>? Should walk in the spirit
of his master plan?</i>

392
00:28:18,710 --> 00:28:20,541
Aunt Mary!

393
00:28:21,580 --> 00:28:23,138
What a nice surprise.

394
00:28:23,215 --> 00:28:24,273
Is it?

395
00:28:24,349 --> 00:28:26,579
I come about
the butler's position.

396
00:28:26,651 --> 00:28:28,881
Oh, good!
Then take these, would you?

397
00:28:28,954 --> 00:28:32,754
And tell Mr. Biddle
that Aunt Mary is here.

398
00:28:32,824 --> 00:28:36,419
And bring us some tea
into the parlor, please.

399
00:28:36,495 --> 00:28:38,520
If the stores get
any more crowded,

400
00:28:38,597 --> 00:28:41,225
I'm just going to have
to give up shopping entirely.

401
00:28:41,299 --> 00:28:44,860
You can't imagine
the swarms of people.

402
00:28:44,936 --> 00:28:47,336
Do sit down, Aunt Mary.

403
00:28:47,406 --> 00:28:49,567
This is not a social call.

404
00:28:49,641 --> 00:28:52,269
I've come for a specific reason.

405
00:28:52,344 --> 00:28:56,144
In today's paper,
in George Gray's gossip column,

406
00:28:56,214 --> 00:28:58,148
it is reported...

407
00:28:59,117 --> 00:29:03,349
that "last week,
Cordelia Drexel Biddle

408
00:29:03,422 --> 00:29:06,914
entered a one-step contest
in Atlantic City

409
00:29:06,992 --> 00:29:10,723
with a Heinie Fenstermaker,"
whoever that is.

410
00:29:10,796 --> 00:29:12,093
I don't recognize the name.

411
00:29:12,164 --> 00:29:14,564
"And won."

412
00:29:16,068 --> 00:29:17,558
We, uh...

413
00:29:18,170 --> 00:29:22,334
We were in Atlantic City
for the Bible-class convention.

414
00:29:22,407 --> 00:29:24,272
I know why
you were in Atlantic City,

415
00:29:24,342 --> 00:29:27,140
but that does not explain
and certainly doesn't excuse

416
00:29:27,212 --> 00:29:28,338
the matter at hand.

417
00:29:28,413 --> 00:29:31,610
Well, good afternoon, Aunt Mary.

418
00:29:33,985 --> 00:29:36,283
Always a pleasure to see you.

419
00:29:37,956 --> 00:29:39,048
Cordelia.

420
00:29:39,124 --> 00:29:40,523
Anthony.

421
00:29:40,592 --> 00:29:41,991
Oh, Anthony, your finger.

422
00:29:42,060 --> 00:29:43,550
Yes.
George bit me.

423
00:29:43,628 --> 00:29:44,287
George?

424
00:29:44,362 --> 00:29:45,989
I can't imagine
what got into him.

425
00:29:46,064 --> 00:29:48,624
Quite obviously
your finger got into him.

426
00:29:48,700 --> 00:29:50,759
Anyone who keeps
an alligator in the house

427
00:29:50,836 --> 00:29:54,101
must expect to be bit
and deserves it.

428
00:29:55,006 --> 00:29:58,305
Well, I'm sure George was only
playing and forgot himself.

429
00:29:58,376 --> 00:29:59,468
Do you really think so?

430
00:29:59,544 --> 00:30:01,011
Oh, I'm sure of it.

431
00:30:02,280 --> 00:30:04,373
Over there, please.

432
00:30:04,449 --> 00:30:07,316
He probably feels
as badly about it as you do.

433
00:30:07,385 --> 00:30:08,909
I wonder.

434
00:30:19,197 --> 00:30:21,290
That will be all, thank you.

435
00:30:21,366 --> 00:30:22,628
You're right, Cordelia.

436
00:30:22,701 --> 00:30:24,692
He wants to make up.

437
00:30:28,273 --> 00:30:29,365
- Well...
- Ha.

438
00:30:29,441 --> 00:30:31,705
If the jungle theatrics
are quite over,

439
00:30:31,776 --> 00:30:34,904
I should like to return to
the subject of my visit,

440
00:30:34,980 --> 00:30:36,311
which is Cordy.

441
00:30:36,381 --> 00:30:37,575
What about Cordy?

442
00:30:37,649 --> 00:30:40,117
I do not consider she's
under the right influences

443
00:30:40,185 --> 00:30:42,176
for a young woman
in her social position.

444
00:30:42,254 --> 00:30:45,280
She's under my influence and
her mother's and her brothers'.

445
00:30:45,357 --> 00:30:47,587
Oh, please, Anthony,
don't pretend naiveté.

446
00:30:47,659 --> 00:30:49,388
You know perfectly well
what I mean.

447
00:30:49,461 --> 00:30:50,621
No, I don't.

448
00:30:50,695 --> 00:30:52,356
I do not know what you mean.

449
00:30:52,430 --> 00:30:54,022
Did you read
this morning's paper?

450
00:30:54,099 --> 00:30:55,862
Yes.
Yes, I did.

451
00:30:55,934 --> 00:30:57,595
German U-boats in our waters

452
00:30:57,669 --> 00:31:00,194
sinking British merchant ships
in sight of Nantucket.

453
00:31:00,272 --> 00:31:02,001
That's what they think
of our neutrality.

454
00:31:02,073 --> 00:31:04,303
Did you get
beyond the first page?

455
00:31:04,376 --> 00:31:06,776
George Gray's column, dear.

456
00:31:06,845 --> 00:31:08,506
Cream or lemon, Aunt Mary?

457
00:31:08,580 --> 00:31:10,411
Of course not.

458
00:31:14,452 --> 00:31:16,579
Blasted professional
troublemaker.

459
00:31:16,655 --> 00:31:18,714
Oh, no, he doesn't make trouble.

460
00:31:18,790 --> 00:31:20,724
He reports it.

461
00:31:21,159 --> 00:31:22,820
This Mr. Fenstermaker.

462
00:31:22,894 --> 00:31:25,522
He's a member of one
of your Bible classes, I assume?

463
00:31:25,597 --> 00:31:26,791
Yes.
Yes, he is.

464
00:31:26,865 --> 00:31:29,265
And a fine, upstanding
young man he is, too.

465
00:31:29,334 --> 00:31:30,961
Anthony, tell me something.

466
00:31:31,036 --> 00:31:34,062
Were the children in school
at all last year?

467
00:31:34,139 --> 00:31:36,972
They were being tutored,
Aunt Mary.

468
00:31:37,475 --> 00:31:39,340
And who's tutoring the tutor?

469
00:31:39,411 --> 00:31:40,378
What do you mean?

470
00:31:40,445 --> 00:31:41,673
Well, everybody knows

471
00:31:41,746 --> 00:31:43,907
that you hired this man
as a boxing coach.

472
00:31:43,982 --> 00:31:45,882
Can't even sign his own name.

473
00:31:45,951 --> 00:31:48,078
Tony and Liv got
into St. Paul's all right.

474
00:31:48,153 --> 00:31:49,484
They're going next week.

475
00:31:49,554 --> 00:31:51,044
And I applaud the move.

476
00:31:51,122 --> 00:31:52,749
Now let's do the same for Cordy.

477
00:31:52,824 --> 00:31:55,190
The Laleta Wingfield School
for Young Ladies

478
00:31:55,260 --> 00:31:58,320
in Lakewood, New Jersey,
is accepting applications.

479
00:31:58,396 --> 00:31:59,795
Oh, no, you don't.

480
00:31:59,864 --> 00:32:02,298
I won't have Cordy
exiled to some prison.

481
00:32:02,367 --> 00:32:03,629
Anthony, answer me.

482
00:32:03,702 --> 00:32:06,000
What proper young man
in his right mind

483
00:32:06,071 --> 00:32:08,164
would want to marry
a lady prizefighter?

484
00:32:08,240 --> 00:32:09,571
Blast the proper young man.

485
00:32:09,641 --> 00:32:10,801
That's easy to say.

486
00:32:10,875 --> 00:32:13,036
Besides, what's this
talk about marriage?

487
00:32:13,111 --> 00:32:14,408
Cordy's a child.

488
00:32:14,479 --> 00:32:16,947
You're blind, Anthony,
in more ways than one.

489
00:32:17,015 --> 00:32:18,812
- Blind or not, I'm not...
- Papa.

490
00:32:18,883 --> 00:32:20,407
Oh, Cordy.

491
00:32:20,485 --> 00:32:22,646
- We were just discussing you.
- Yes, I know.

492
00:32:22,721 --> 00:32:26,282
And, Papa, I'd like
to go off to school.

493
00:32:26,358 --> 00:32:27,586
Hello, Aunt Mary.

494
00:32:27,659 --> 00:32:28,990
Good afternoon, Cordelia.

495
00:32:29,060 --> 00:32:30,084
Hello, Mama.

496
00:32:30,161 --> 00:32:31,389
Darling.

497
00:32:31,463 --> 00:32:32,521
Cordy.

498
00:32:32,597 --> 00:32:34,326
Did I hear you correctly?

499
00:32:34,399 --> 00:32:36,799
I'm sure you did, Papa.

500
00:32:37,369 --> 00:32:39,929
Are you still upset
about what happened a while ago?

501
00:32:40,005 --> 00:32:41,836
Do you want that boy
back over here?

502
00:32:41,906 --> 00:32:43,066
I'll drag him back.

503
00:32:43,141 --> 00:32:46,110
No, Papa.
It isn't Charlie Taylor.

504
00:32:46,177 --> 00:32:47,405
Well, then, what is it?

505
00:32:47,479 --> 00:32:48,810
Don't you like it here?

506
00:32:48,880 --> 00:32:50,142
Of course I like it here.

507
00:32:50,215 --> 00:32:51,739
Don't we have a good time?

508
00:32:51,816 --> 00:32:53,010
Yes.

509
00:32:53,652 --> 00:32:57,053
But it's hard to explain, Papa.

510
00:32:57,122 --> 00:32:59,283
I'm not like the other girls.

511
00:32:59,357 --> 00:33:00,619
Well, hooray for that.

512
00:33:00,692 --> 00:33:02,023
Look at the other girls.

513
00:33:02,093 --> 00:33:02,923
Oh, Papa.

514
00:33:02,994 --> 00:33:05,462
Cordy,
I like you the way you are.

515
00:33:05,530 --> 00:33:06,462
You're pretty.

516
00:33:06,531 --> 00:33:08,123
You have fun.
You're alive.

517
00:33:08,199 --> 00:33:10,599
You've got a better
left hook than Tony or Liv.

518
00:33:10,669 --> 00:33:13,797
But I don't want a left hook.

519
00:33:13,872 --> 00:33:17,364
Anthony, I think we'd better
talk about this later.

520
00:33:17,442 --> 00:33:19,535
She doesn't know
what she's saying.

521
00:33:19,611 --> 00:33:22,375
I do know what I'm saying.

522
00:33:22,714 --> 00:33:26,047
I want to go to
Miss Wingfield's school.

523
00:33:27,719 --> 00:33:28,981
All right.

524
00:33:29,054 --> 00:33:30,817
All right.
You go.

525
00:33:31,356 --> 00:33:33,347
Go to prison if you want to.

526
00:33:40,398 --> 00:33:42,195
Thank you, Papa.

527
00:33:47,839 --> 00:33:49,306
Blast!

528
00:33:50,709 --> 00:33:52,870
Ooh!

529
00:33:55,113 --> 00:33:57,547
Well, it's late.

530
00:33:57,615 --> 00:33:59,981
And I've other things to do.

531
00:34:00,051 --> 00:34:02,713
Well, thank you
for coming, Aunt Mary.

532
00:34:03,154 --> 00:34:04,985
I don't like to interfere.

533
00:34:07,158 --> 00:34:10,855
But attention must be paid
to these matters.

534
00:34:11,429 --> 00:34:12,862
I know.

535
00:34:12,931 --> 00:34:14,762
Good day, Cordelia.

536
00:34:16,167 --> 00:34:17,498
Good day, Anthony.

537
00:34:38,790 --> 00:34:40,018
Anthony.

538
00:34:40,091 --> 00:34:43,083
We do have to let Cordy go.

539
00:34:43,561 --> 00:34:45,358
She's not a child anymore.

540
00:34:45,430 --> 00:34:49,662
And it's selfish to keep her
here in this special world.

541
00:34:49,734 --> 00:34:51,702
What's wrong
with this special world?

542
00:34:51,770 --> 00:34:55,206
Oh, Anthony, why do you have to
take everything so personally?

543
00:34:55,273 --> 00:34:57,138
Is there some other way?

544
00:34:58,276 --> 00:35:00,767
You might as well put out
that terrible weed.

545
00:35:00,845 --> 00:35:03,075
You won't get rid
of me that way.

546
00:35:14,192 --> 00:35:15,682
Anthony.

547
00:35:15,760 --> 00:35:17,591
I raised very few objections

548
00:35:17,662 --> 00:35:19,721
to the way that Cordy's
been brought up,

549
00:35:19,798 --> 00:35:23,393
despite its being
rather unorthodox.

550
00:35:23,468 --> 00:35:25,936
Don't say, "What's wrong
with being unorthodox?"

551
00:35:26,004 --> 00:35:27,972
There's nothing wrong with it.

552
00:35:28,039 --> 00:35:29,267
If I didn't feel that way,

553
00:35:29,340 --> 00:35:32,332
I couldn't have stayed married
to you all these years.

554
00:35:32,710 --> 00:35:34,109
It's been a good life.

555
00:35:34,179 --> 00:35:37,273
A healthy life.
And Cordy's been happy.

556
00:35:37,348 --> 00:35:41,842
But now she's older
and feels a need to reach out.

557
00:35:41,920 --> 00:35:43,785
But she won't like it.

558
00:35:44,289 --> 00:35:46,689
That's for her to decide.

559
00:35:47,959 --> 00:35:50,655
You didn't want to let go
of Tony and Liv.

560
00:35:50,728 --> 00:35:53,788
You fought St. Paul's
like a tiger.

561
00:35:54,299 --> 00:35:56,995
Well, now it's Cordy.

562
00:35:57,068 --> 00:35:58,126
Blast it, Cordelia.

563
00:35:58,203 --> 00:36:00,569
I said she could go, didn't I?

564
00:36:00,839 --> 00:36:02,033
Yes, dear.

565
00:36:02,106 --> 00:36:03,471
Well, then...

566
00:36:04,142 --> 00:36:06,076
what's all the fuss about?

567
00:36:10,348 --> 00:36:12,077
I'm going out to the gym.

568
00:36:12,150 --> 00:36:13,117
Good idea.

569
00:36:13,184 --> 00:36:15,448
You'll feel much better
when you get back.

570
00:36:19,491 --> 00:36:21,186
Oh.
Mrs. Biddle.

571
00:36:21,259 --> 00:36:23,386
Mrs. Biddle,
if it's convenient...

572
00:36:23,461 --> 00:36:26,191
Oh, yes. I'm afraid
I don't remember your name.

573
00:36:26,264 --> 00:36:27,458
John Lawless, ma'am.

574
00:36:27,532 --> 00:36:29,056
The Mayflower Employment Agency.

575
00:36:29,133 --> 00:36:32,125
Ah, fine.
Dinner's at 7:00, John.

576
00:36:34,305 --> 00:36:35,237
Well?

577
00:36:35,306 --> 00:36:36,500
Were you put on?

578
00:36:36,574 --> 00:36:38,804
"Dinner's at 7:00," she says.

579
00:36:38,877 --> 00:36:39,901
Heaven help me.

580
00:36:57,028 --> 00:36:59,189
Good way to let off steam.

581
00:36:59,764 --> 00:37:03,598
Papa, I'm sorry
for the way I acted.

582
00:37:03,668 --> 00:37:05,659
I appreciate your apology.

583
00:37:05,737 --> 00:37:06,761
I do love my home.

584
00:37:06,838 --> 00:37:09,500
I don't really want to go away.

585
00:37:09,574 --> 00:37:11,701
Well, you were right
wanting to go.

586
00:37:11,776 --> 00:37:13,744
You're not a child any longer.

587
00:37:13,811 --> 00:37:17,474
It's selfish to try to keep you
here in this special world.

588
00:37:18,283 --> 00:37:20,274
What's wrong
with this special world?

589
00:37:20,351 --> 00:37:22,649
Now, don't you start that.

590
00:37:25,757 --> 00:37:27,019
Cordy.

591
00:37:29,994 --> 00:37:32,895
You have to make your own life
in your own way.

592
00:37:32,964 --> 00:37:35,956
You can't stay here
with your mother and me forever.

593
00:37:37,936 --> 00:37:39,801
Of course, when you
come home on vacations,

594
00:37:39,871 --> 00:37:42,032
things will be just the same.

595
00:37:46,711 --> 00:37:49,202
All of a sudden, I'm afraid.

596
00:37:49,881 --> 00:37:52,042
Now, that I won't have.

597
00:37:52,116 --> 00:37:54,380
There's nothing out there
to be afraid of,

598
00:37:54,452 --> 00:37:56,818
as long as you keep your
guard up and your chin tucked,

599
00:37:56,888 --> 00:38:00,016
and know how to bring one up
from the floor.

600
00:38:01,125 --> 00:38:03,218
Oh, Papa.

601
00:38:04,495 --> 00:38:06,690
When I was a little girl,

602
00:38:06,764 --> 00:38:09,392
I used to think you must be
the most wonderful person

603
00:38:09,467 --> 00:38:11,298
in the whole world.

604
00:38:13,204 --> 00:38:18,972
Now that I'm older
and much wiser, I know you are.

605
00:38:22,180 --> 00:38:25,547
Well, come on,
let's go back in the house.

606
00:38:28,920 --> 00:38:32,856
If you don't like that school,
you don't have to stay up there.

607
00:38:33,591 --> 00:38:35,752
<i>? Dee-a da da da?</i>

608
00:38:35,893 --> 00:38:37,827
<i>? Dee-a ta ta ta-ta ta?</i>

609
00:38:37,895 --> 00:38:38,987
<i>? Da-da ta-ta tee?</i>

610
00:38:47,639 --> 00:38:49,038
Mr. Biddle?

611
00:38:59,017 --> 00:39:00,450
Mr. Bid...

612
00:39:27,278 --> 00:39:29,007
What's wrong?
You're white as a sheet.

613
00:39:29,080 --> 00:39:30,945
Faith, you do have an alligator!

614
00:39:31,015 --> 00:39:32,676
12 of them.
What's wrong with that?

615
00:39:32,750 --> 00:39:34,342
Not a thing.
It's relieved, I am.

616
00:39:34,419 --> 00:39:36,819
I captured them myself
down in Florida.

617
00:39:36,888 --> 00:39:39,823
Went into the swamp
with a party of Seminoles.

618
00:39:39,891 --> 00:39:42,553
Have you ever seen a Seminole
Indian capture alligators?

619
00:39:42,627 --> 00:39:43,753
I can't say I have.

620
00:39:43,828 --> 00:39:48,128
Well, they can paddle a canoe so
you can't hear it two feet away.

621
00:39:48,199 --> 00:39:49,757
If the animals
don't show themselves,

622
00:39:49,834 --> 00:39:51,529
you give them the mating call.

623
00:40:01,312 --> 00:40:02,677
Say, who are you, anyway?

624
00:40:02,747 --> 00:40:04,738
John Lawless, sir.
I'll be the new butler.

625
00:40:04,816 --> 00:40:06,408
Oh, we've got a new butler.

626
00:40:06,484 --> 00:40:07,917
No, Papa.
He quit.

627
00:40:07,985 --> 00:40:09,179
Already?

628
00:40:09,253 --> 00:40:10,584
- Days ago.
- Oh.

629
00:40:10,655 --> 00:40:12,418
Well, if you'll excuse me, sir.

630
00:40:12,490 --> 00:40:14,321
John Lawless, is it?

631
00:40:14,392 --> 00:40:15,916
That's right, sir.

632
00:40:15,993 --> 00:40:17,392
Tell me, John.

633
00:40:17,462 --> 00:40:18,986
Are you a religious man?

634
00:40:19,063 --> 00:40:20,553
I try to live by the Good Book.

635
00:40:20,631 --> 00:40:22,462
How well do you succeed?

636
00:40:22,533 --> 00:40:24,228
- I'm not sure.
- Never mind.

637
00:40:24,302 --> 00:40:26,702
We'll go into that another time.

638
00:40:26,771 --> 00:40:28,466
What do you think of boxing?

639
00:40:28,806 --> 00:40:31,001
- Boxing?
- Why don't we find Mother...

640
00:40:31,075 --> 00:40:33,475
Not in self-defense.
Ever done any of that?

641
00:40:33,544 --> 00:40:35,671
Well, at the fair last year
in County Tyrone,

642
00:40:35,747 --> 00:40:38,682
I was fisticuffs champion.

643
00:40:39,217 --> 00:40:40,707
Is that so?

644
00:40:40,785 --> 00:40:41,717
Champion?

645
00:40:41,786 --> 00:40:43,811
Well, it isn't
a very large county, sir.

646
00:40:43,888 --> 00:40:47,016
Fisticuffs champion
of where was that again?

647
00:40:47,091 --> 00:40:49,321
County Tyrone.
It's in Ireland.

648
00:40:49,393 --> 00:40:52,226
Ah. You going to become
an American citizen, John?

649
00:40:52,296 --> 00:40:54,958
- Well, I intend to apply, sir.
- You'll never regret it.

650
00:40:55,032 --> 00:40:56,829
- Greatest country in the world.
- Papa!

651
00:40:56,901 --> 00:40:59,597
There's certain things
I believe in, John.

652
00:40:59,670 --> 00:41:02,537
God and the United States
are at the top of the list.

653
00:41:02,607 --> 00:41:05,474
I know very well what
the United States has to offer.

654
00:41:05,543 --> 00:41:06,771
That's how it is I'm here.

655
00:41:06,844 --> 00:41:08,141
Yes, well, like I say...

656
00:41:08,212 --> 00:41:10,009
There's something else
I know just as well.

657
00:41:10,081 --> 00:41:13,016
And that is you are what you
are, and that's good, too.

658
00:41:13,084 --> 00:41:15,143
I beg your pardon?

659
00:41:15,219 --> 00:41:17,278
Well, being an American
is addin' something.

660
00:41:17,355 --> 00:41:19,255
It isn't subtracting.

661
00:41:21,392 --> 00:41:23,121
On the night
before I sailed away,

662
00:41:23,194 --> 00:41:25,526
they come from far and near.

663
00:41:25,596 --> 00:41:27,655
<i>? All me friends
and all me kin?</i>

664
00:41:27,732 --> 00:41:30,997
<i>? To shed a partin' tear?</i>

665
00:41:31,068 --> 00:41:33,832
<i>? We knew we'd
never meet again?</i>

666
00:41:33,905 --> 00:41:38,137
<i>? And yet was clear to see?</i>

667
00:41:38,209 --> 00:41:41,975
<i>? I'd always be
a part of them?</i>

668
00:41:42,046 --> 00:41:48,884
<i>? And them a part of me?</i>

669
00:41:49,854 --> 00:41:52,220
<i>? I'll always be Irish?</i>

670
00:41:52,290 --> 00:41:54,155
<i>? 'Cause that's how I began?</i>

671
00:41:54,225 --> 00:41:57,353
<i>? I'll always be Irish,
I'll say that to any man?</i>

672
00:41:57,428 --> 00:42:01,194
<i>? And when I'm an American,
I'll be a good one, too?</i>

673
00:42:01,265 --> 00:42:04,632
<i>? I'll be truly as American
as Irish stew?</i>

674
00:42:04,702 --> 00:42:06,431
Hey, that's pretty good.

675
00:42:06,504 --> 00:42:10,133
<i>? He'll be truly as American
as Irish stew?</i>

676
00:42:10,208 --> 00:42:12,574
Ask for Irish stew in Ireland
and see what you get.

677
00:42:12,643 --> 00:42:13,871
I never thought of that.

678
00:42:13,945 --> 00:42:17,403
In Ireland,
all the stew is Irish.

679
00:42:18,015 --> 00:42:19,744
<i>? I'll always be Irish?</i>

680
00:42:19,817 --> 00:42:21,546
<i>? A fact I'll not deny?</i>

681
00:42:21,619 --> 00:42:25,248
<i>? I'll always be Irish,
and I'll hold me head up high?</i>

682
00:42:25,323 --> 00:42:27,223
<i>? I'll wear the green
St. Patty's Day?</i>

683
00:42:27,291 --> 00:42:28,758
<i>? And yet for all of that?</i>

684
00:42:28,826 --> 00:42:31,920
<i>? I'll be truly as American
as "Casey at the Bat"?</i>

685
00:42:31,996 --> 00:42:36,899
<i>? He'll be truly as American
as "Casey at the Bat"?</i>

686
00:42:37,668 --> 00:42:40,034
Say, that looks like
good exercise.

687
00:42:42,773 --> 00:42:43,705
Come on, Cordy.

688
00:42:43,774 --> 00:42:45,571
- Hey!
- Papa!

689
00:42:45,643 --> 00:42:46,940
If you can win
a one-step contest,

690
00:42:47,011 --> 00:42:48,239
you ought to be able to do this.

691
00:42:48,312 --> 00:42:49,643
I thought you
didn't like dancing.

692
00:42:49,714 --> 00:42:51,511
It's that waltzing business
I don't like.

693
00:42:51,582 --> 00:42:54,016
Ha.
That's for old folks.

694
00:42:58,089 --> 00:42:59,147
Hey!

695
00:43:01,158 --> 00:43:02,716
Huh! Ha!

696
00:43:09,267 --> 00:43:11,326
<i>? If I went to Paris
for the rest of me days?</i>

697
00:43:11,402 --> 00:43:13,302
<i>? And ate bread and cheese
in sidewalk cafés?</i>

698
00:43:13,371 --> 00:43:14,895
<i>? Lived in a garret,
wore a beret?</i>

699
00:43:14,972 --> 00:43:17,805
<i>-? What would I be??
- An Irishman!</i>

700
00:43:22,146 --> 00:43:24,080
<i>? If I went to Tibet
and bought me a yak?</i>

701
00:43:24,148 --> 00:43:25,843
<i>? And traveled Siberia
ridin' his back?</i>

702
00:43:25,917 --> 00:43:27,748
<i>? The peasants would point
at me, what would they say??</i>

703
00:43:27,818 --> 00:43:31,379
Irishman?

704
00:43:31,455 --> 00:43:33,218
- Right!
- Right!

705
00:43:34,492 --> 00:43:39,828
<i>? But if I went to Spain
and grew a moustache?</i>

706
00:43:39,897 --> 00:43:44,766
<i>? Strummed the guitar
and wore me a sash?</i>

707
00:43:44,835 --> 00:43:50,569
<i>? Became a toreador
and fought me a bull?</i>

708
00:43:50,641 --> 00:43:51,903
<i>- ndele!</i>

709
00:43:51,976 --> 00:43:53,739
<i>- Ndele!</i>

710
00:44:11,529 --> 00:44:13,326
- Hooray!
- Yippee!

711
00:44:13,931 --> 00:44:15,956
After they awarded me
both ears and the tail,

712
00:44:16,033 --> 00:44:16,965
what would they say?

713
00:44:17,034 --> 00:44:17,966
<i>- Olé!
- Olé!</i>

714
00:44:18,035 --> 00:44:20,333
- For the Irishman!
- Right!

715
00:44:20,404 --> 00:44:22,235
Hey-ho!

716
00:44:22,306 --> 00:44:24,934
Whoo-aaa-hoo!

717
00:44:28,279 --> 00:44:30,042
Come on, Mrs. Worth.

718
00:44:30,114 --> 00:44:31,081
Come on, now.

719
00:44:31,148 --> 00:44:32,342
Whoo! Ha!

720
00:44:32,416 --> 00:44:34,111
It's good for you.

721
00:44:37,154 --> 00:44:38,519
Ha ha!

722
00:44:39,256 --> 00:44:41,884
Ah, thatagirl!

723
00:44:45,763 --> 00:44:48,129
You should have seen
me father doin' this.

724
00:44:48,199 --> 00:44:51,396
Like a tornado across the floor.

725
00:44:51,469 --> 00:44:52,458
Hey!

726
00:44:54,705 --> 00:44:55,637
Oh!

727
00:44:55,706 --> 00:44:57,105
Ohhhh!

728
00:44:57,174 --> 00:44:59,108
Ohh! Oh!

729
00:44:59,176 --> 00:45:00,700
<i>? He'll always be Irish?</i>

730
00:45:00,778 --> 00:45:02,405
Ah, shout it good and loud!

731
00:45:02,480 --> 00:45:04,539
<i>? He'll always be Irish?</i>

732
00:45:04,615 --> 00:45:07,175
<i>? Of his heritage, he's proud?</i>

733
00:45:07,251 --> 00:45:11,449
<i>? I'm proud of Irish blarney?</i>

734
00:45:11,522 --> 00:45:17,085
<i>? And Irish sentiment?</i>

735
00:45:17,161 --> 00:45:20,756
<i>? And I'll bet someday
we get an Irish president?</i>

736
00:45:20,831 --> 00:45:25,461
<i>? And I'll bet someday
we get an Irish president?</i>

737
00:45:25,936 --> 00:45:28,029
Whee-ha!

738
00:45:30,908 --> 00:45:32,876
Hey, let me in there.

739
00:45:34,412 --> 00:45:36,141
Hey-ya diddle!

740
00:45:37,415 --> 00:45:38,347
Hey-ya!

741
00:45:38,416 --> 00:45:39,781
Ha!

742
00:45:44,488 --> 00:45:45,512
Beautiful!

743
00:45:45,589 --> 00:45:47,056
Whee!

744
00:45:57,368 --> 00:45:58,960
