02:45:30,200 --> 02:45:32,293
Who would be dropping by
this afternoon?

2805
02:45:32,369 --> 02:45:33,461
I can't imagine.

2806
02:45:33,536 --> 02:45:35,834
Hardly anybody lives here
anymore.

2807
02:45:39,542 --> 02:45:41,203
The tea will be a moment.

2808
02:45:41,278 --> 02:45:44,304
Mrs. Worth's icing up
a gorgeous chocolate cake.

2809
02:45:47,717 --> 02:45:49,344
Come in, gentlemen.

2810
02:45:49,886 --> 02:45:52,047
Sir, is Mr. Biddle at home?

2811
02:45:52,455 --> 02:45:54,889
Yes.
Will you come this way, please?

2812
02:45:54,958 --> 02:45:57,085
There's some gentlemen
to see you, sir.

2813
02:45:57,160 --> 02:45:58,149
Well, look who's here.

2814
02:45:58,228 --> 02:45:59,286
- Mr. Biddle.
- Lieutenant.

2815
02:45:59,362 --> 02:46:02,297
- Mr. Biddle.
- Good to see you.

2816
02:46:02,365 --> 02:46:05,095
Sir, a set of orders have been
received at our headquarters

2817
02:46:05,168 --> 02:46:07,136
concerning your future relations
with the Corps.

2818
02:46:07,203 --> 02:46:10,570
And we felt that these orders
warranted personal delivery.

2819
02:46:23,586 --> 02:46:24,553
I don't believe it.

2820
02:46:24,621 --> 02:46:25,986
Anthony, what is it?

2821
02:46:26,056 --> 02:46:28,183
When I tried to enlist,
they turned me down.

2822
02:46:28,258 --> 02:46:29,987
Said I was too old
for active service.

2823
02:46:30,060 --> 02:46:31,459
Anthony, for heaven's sake.

2824
02:46:31,528 --> 02:46:34,554
Cordelia, I've been awarded
a provisional captaincy

2825
02:46:34,631 --> 02:46:35,757
in the Marine Corps.

2826
02:46:35,832 --> 02:46:37,697
I'm ordered to report
to Parris Island.

2827
02:46:37,767 --> 02:46:39,257
- Congratulations, sir.
- Thank you.

2828
02:46:39,336 --> 02:46:40,769
Congratulations, Mr. Biddle.

2829
02:46:40,837 --> 02:46:43,101
- John!
- Yes, sir?

2830
02:46:43,506 --> 02:46:44,837
John, we're in the Marines.

2831
02:46:44,908 --> 02:46:46,068
- We are, sir?
- Yes.

2832
02:46:46,142 --> 02:46:48,167
Bring out some of that
good Madeira, will you?

2833
02:46:48,244 --> 02:46:49,575
You know, gentlemen,

2834
02:46:49,646 --> 02:46:52,774
there's something to which I've
been giving a lot of thought.

2835
02:46:52,849 --> 02:46:55,545
The French and the British have
been in this war for some time.

2836
02:46:55,618 --> 02:46:57,848
They must have perfected
close-combat techniques

2837
02:46:57,921 --> 02:46:59,684
which are more realistic
than ours.

2838
02:46:59,756 --> 02:47:02,020
I feel that we ought to send
someone over there

2839
02:47:02,092 --> 02:47:03,457
to observe and learn.

2840
02:47:03,526 --> 02:47:05,824
Anthony, I don't think
that somebody

2841
02:47:05,895 --> 02:47:08,420
who's been in the Marines
for less than five minutes

2842
02:47:08,498 --> 02:47:10,432
should be trying to decide
Corps policy.

2843
02:47:10,500 --> 02:47:12,434
He's sure to end up
running things, Mrs. Biddle.

2844
02:47:12,502 --> 02:47:14,834
He might as well start off
that way.

2845
02:47:15,905 --> 02:47:17,338
Oh, thank you, John.

2846
02:47:17,407 --> 02:47:19,739
You should've brought one
for yourself.

2847
02:47:21,878 --> 02:47:23,607
I'm not much at making speeches.

2848
02:47:23,680 --> 02:47:26,706
But I guess you know
how we all feel about this.

2849
02:47:26,783 --> 02:47:28,114
Mr. Biddle has landed.

2850
02:47:28,184 --> 02:47:30,015
And the Marines are
well in hand.

2851
02:47:30,086 --> 02:47:30,848
Right?

2852
